          "title": "Total obedience — Noah's faith in action",
          "body": "The chapter's final verse is its simplest and most powerful: 'Thus Noah did; according to all that God had commanded him, so he did.' The repetition — Moses says it twice in one sentence — is emphatic. There is no record of Noah arguing, negotiating, questioning the design specifications, or asking for a sign that the flood would actually come. In a world where 'every intent of every heart was only evil continually' (6:5), one man simply did what God said. Hebrews 11:7 gives the theological interpretation: 'By faith Noah, being warned by God about things not yet seen, in reverence prepared an ark for the salvation of his household, by which he condemned the world, and became an heir of the righteousness which is according to faith.' The obedience is faith made visible. James 2:17-18 would later argue that faith without works is dead — Noah is the Genesis exhibit for that argument. He believed the unseen flood (6:17) and the unfulfilled covenant (6:18), and his belief produced one specific act sustained over years: he built the ark."
