        "number": 3,
        "title": "But Noah — grace as the hinge of history",
        "range": "6:8-10",
        "excerpt": "But Noah found favor in the eyes of the LORD. Noah was a righteous man, blameless in his time; Noah walked with God.",
        "body": "The 'but' of verse 8 is one of the most consequential conjunctions in Scripture. Six verses of relentless indictment — universal wickedness, divine grief, judicial sentence — and then: 'But Noah found favor in the eyes of the LORD.' The *waw adversative* in Hebrew pivots the entire chapter. Humanity is under sentence; one man is under grace.\n\nThe grammar of this sequence is theologically decisive. Moses records that Noah *found favor* (6:8) before he describes Noah as righteous and blameless (6:9). This is not literary carelessness — it is the canonical pattern of grace preceding and grounding righteousness. Noah does not find favor because he is righteous; he is righteous because he lives in the orbit of God's favor. The New Testament makes the pattern explicit: 'you did not choose Me, but I chose you' (John 15:16); 'those whom He foreknew, He also predestined' (Romans 8:29). The Reformed tradition (Calvin, *Commentary on Genesis* 6:8) reads Noah's favor as sovereign election; the Arminian tradition reads it as God's foreknowledge of Noah's responsiveness. Both agree that the grace-righteousness order is grace-first.\n\nVerse 9 then gives Noah's three-part portrait: righteous (*tsaddiq*), blameless (*tamim*), walked with God (*halakh et-ha-elohim*). *Tsaddiq* denotes conformity to the standard of right relationship — legally, morally, relationally right before God and neighbor. *Tamim* is the wholeness-word used of sacrificial animals without blemish (Leviticus 1:3) and of Abraham's call to personal integrity (Genesis 17:1). Together they describe not sinless perfection but moral integrity — a man whose life runs in the direction of God's character, not away from it. The third descriptor, 'walked with God,' uses the identical formula applied to Enoch in Genesis 5:22, 24. Enoch walked with God and was taken; Noah walks with God and will be saved through water. The formula in both cases describes sustained, habitual fellowship — a life oriented toward God as its reference point.\n\nVerse 10's note that Noah fathered Shem, Ham, and Japheth is not incidental. The grace extended to Noah is already reaching beyond him to his family — the covenant of 6:18 will explicitly include 'your sons, your wife, and your sons' wives.' Redemption is never merely individual; it has household and, in Noah's case, civilizational reach."
